Boil a #kettle{}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2} (peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pour the boiled water into a #large saucepan{} with @salt{0.5%tsp} on high heat.

Add the @Orzo{180%grams} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{10%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @Diced Chorizo{120%grams} and fry until it starts to brown, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Lower the heat, then stir in the garlic, @Tomato Puree{30%grams} and @Cajun Spice Mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder). Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

> Cajun spice mix contains ingredients such as chilli powder, ground cumin, oregano and thyme.

Add the @Chicken Stock Paste{10%grams}, @Honey{1%tbsp} and @Water for the Sauce{100%ml} to the chorizo. Stir to combine and bring to the boil.

Simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, add the @Peas{120%grams} and simmer until piping hot, ~{1%minute}.

Stir through the cooked orzo and @Creme Fraiche{75%grams}. Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat.

Stir through the @Grated Hard Italian Style Cheese{20%grams} until melted. Taste and season with @salt and @pepper if needed.

Share the creamy Cajun chorizo orzo between your serving bowls.

Sprinkle over the @Crispy Onions{1%sachet} to finish.

Enjoy!